            <Title>Ambush-Mandrameen</Title>
            <Synopsis>Theives ambush gold caravan in the desert. A witch conjures storm to help them. Caravan has a mage, but storm strikes down mage before he can kill thieves. Turns out not to be a gold train - was a setup - The man who set them up? Salavan Saran.</Synopsis>
            <Text>The poet Melrameen, upon giving up the craft, said that every artist who has tried to capture the beauty of Nature has failed. For him it was a simple matter of fact: art is seduction, its purpose is to divert attention away from what is really there to what the artist wants you to see - but nothing is more seductive than Nature. Nothing can match its grandeur and complexity at scale, for inside every leaf, rock, cloud, and tree are systems within systems, patterns within patterns for as far as it is possible to look. 
Up or down, big or small, the shock of this beauty is everwhere and it goes straight to the spinal cord. If the mood is right, it hits with an intensity that no poet or painter could hope to achieve. There’s no point in trying.
Melrameen’s son, Mandrameen, disagreed. When he did, Mel told him to go out into the Sand and see for himself, to follow in the footsteps of the Jeketian Fathers. There the desert heat would pull his dreaming mind out from his body, like a cork from a bottle, and if he lingered in the sun near to death, then all his schemes and fantasies would evaporate. Nature’s beauty would fill the void and confront him with the truth about the edge between himself and the Universe.
Mel didn’t use so many words, but that was what he meant. And he didn’t think his son would actually do it, but at the age of eighteen, Mandrameen did. He ran out into the Sand. 
Three days later Mandri was near to death, just as his father had wanted. In his final hours he took up shelter under a karkle bush and just laid there as his toungue dried out and shrivled. 
Then a man - a giant of a man - found him in that gully. 
That man was Ayram.
Then and there, Mandri became an Ayramun.
That was all that Mandrameen cared to write about the day that Ayram saved his life. He was more thorough with the testimonies of his fellow Ayramun. He’d corner them whenever he could to get the story of their life before meeting Ayram. The best time to do it, Mandri found, was out on the morning watch. 
There was plenty of time then because morning did not come all at once to the Junei Plain. There the sun rises behind a coastal mountain range called the Blackshells. These mighty peaks guard a jagged blade of night from the approach of day. As the sun climbs up into the sky, and as its rays flood down into the plain, the mountains’ shadow slowly retreats to reveal a glowing sea of pink sand dunes, white gypsum, and salt. It’s not until three hands to noon that daylight reaches the pebbled foothills of the Blackshells themselves. It then creeps up the mountain slopes until at last, four fingers to midday, the whole of the Sand is lit.
Its not until then that heat gets into the air and kicks up a blistering wind, one which bakes the Earth like a furnace. There aren’t many hides or holes that can keep out this heat, but the closer you are to the peaks the longer you have till it gets to you - the longer you have to wake up. Up there, the Ayramun sleep for a good long while, giving Mandri plenty of time to pester his watch-partner about their history.
Today’s watch was with Seculla. She and Mandrameen were sitting atop a black cliff that overlooked the Junei pass. Below this cliff was a red clay road. Running east, the road disappeared into the mountains until eventually it came to the little port of Mudwater. Running west, the road wound around hills, black screes, and outcrops of rock until it came to the Junei Plain, and from there, it ran straight as an arrow to the horizon. 
It all made Mandri feel like a regular brigand. There they were, dwelling in the shadows, eyeing the brilliant plain with a fearful and jealous , searching for any sign of their quarry.
But the plain was was empty as far as Mandrameen could see.
Seculla’s eyes were better.
“Do you see them?” Mandri asked.
“I see nothing”, Seculla said, “I heard it’ll be another, I don’t know, two hands until they show up.”
“Two hands,” Mandrameen repeated. “That’s not so bad. In the meantime -”
“No.” 
“Why not?” Mandrameen asked. “What else is there to do?”
“I’ve told you a hundred times - I don’t want to talk about it.”
“Your past is as important as any other,” Mandrameen said. “More important, even. Outside of Pella you’ve been with Ayram the longest.”
“It’s not important.”
Mandrameen pulled a few dried figs from a pocket he’d sewn into his shirt and started to munch on them.
